          <span class="icon icon-text"></span>
          NATO Review
        </h1>
      </header>    
                  
        <ul class="js-slider cf" data-slider-items="1|1|1">
            
            <!-- /cps/en/natohq/134415.htm -->
            
            
            


            <li class="js-slider-item">                        
                <div class="box-media box-media--stretched"> 
                    <a href="http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2016/Also-in-2016/nato-deterrence-defence-alliance/EN/index.htm">
                    <img data-lazy="/nato_static_fl2014/assets/pictures/stock_2016/160811-NR-Anakonda_rdax_375x250.jpg" alt="" />
                    </a>
                </div>                        
                <div class="box-content">
                  <ul class="list-arrowed list-arrowed--v2"> 
                    <li>                         
                      <span class="teaser-title">                            
                        <a href="http://www.nato.int/docu/review/2016/Also-in-2016/nato-deterrence-defence-alliance/EN/index.htm">
                        On Deterrence
                        </a>
                      </span>                           
                      <span class="date date--block">05 Aug. 2016</span>                                                    
                      <span class="teaser-txt">Deterrence is back. After the end of the Cold War, the Alliance focused less on territorial defence and more on out-of-area crisis management, first in the western Balkans and later also in Afghanistan. That changed in 2014 because of concerns about Russia’s aggressive actions towards Ukraine as well as the rise of so-called Islamic State (or Daesh) in Syria and Iraq.</span>  
                    </li>
                  </ul>                      
                </div>
            </li>
            
        </ul>
         
